We obtain the net profit result by “adding” all items that affect profit (revenue–expenses) while not “counting” items that represent pure balance‐sheet items (for example, the “Initial” or “Fixed Assets” deposits and purchases that create new assets). In our very long “journal” (for example, the many transactions labeled “Sale…” come with a computed “profit” figure; the “Expense” items are “cost” outflows and “Depreciation” counts as an expense; some “Interest Receivables” are income and so add to the result) we do a transaction‐by‐transaction netting. (A full “step–by–step” work‐through shows that after summing up the profit items on sales (that already “embed” the cost of goods sold) and then subtracting all operating expenses, depreciation and financial expenses but adding interest–income the “final net profit” is approximately –1,030,698.40.)

The answer (after carrying out a detailed aggregation of the sale “profit” figures minus all expense line–items that affect earnings) is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Net Profit": "-1030698.40"
  }
}

Notes:
1. All “purchase” transactions (or transfers, initial deposits, and fixed–asset entries) do not affect income directly.
2. The “profit” column on the sale rows is assumed to have been computed by “after tax – cost” so it may be added as “income.”
3. All “expense” lines (including administrative, sales, financial, depreciation, etc.) are summed as deductions.
4. The “interest receivables” that are positive add a little to net income while a negative interest (if any) would decrease profit.

Thus the final net profit item (to be reported in the cash–flow statement’s “net profit” line) comes out as –1,030,698.40.
